articles.content:
What is nature? Nature is existence—the sum of that which is. It is usually
called “nature” when we think of it as a system of interconnected, interacting
entities governed by law. So “nature” really means the universe of entities
acting and interacting in accordance with their identities.
articles.attribution:
Leonard Peikoff, 
The Philosophy of Objectivism lecture series, Lecture 2
